# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: baseball-positions
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:baseball-positions/16-inch-softball] The first set of rules was published in 1937 by the Amateur Softball Association, in the same manual as the rules for fastpitch softball.
[src:baseball-positions/16-inch-softball] Game play for 16-inch softball is mostly consistent with standard softball game play.
[src:baseball-positions/16-inch-softball] In contrast to standard, or 12-inch (30.48 cm) softball, it is played with a ball 16 inches (40.64 cm) in circumference.
[src:baseball-positions/16-inch-softball] It is common to see higher arched pitching, and balls/strikes are determined by where the ball lands and crosses the batter's body.
[src:baseball-positions/16-inch-softball] Leagues may form co-ed, all-male, or all-female teams.
[src:baseball-positions/16-inch-softball] Additionally, teams may choose competitive or recreational leagues.
[src:baseball-positions/16-inch-softball] There may be rule variations associated with the specific field or league of play.
[src:baseball-positions/16-inch-softball] When playing in a co-ed league, there may be other rules that relate to the male-to-female ratio of team members and batting order.
[src:baseball-positions/16-inch-softball] The National Softball Association (NSA) also has a published set of rules governing 16-inch softball play.
[src:baseball-positions/16-inch-softball] The earliest known softball game of any kind was played at the Farragut Boat Club in Chicago on Thanksgiving Day 1887.
[src:baseball-positions/16-inch-softball] The first softball was a wrapped up boxing glove and the bat was a broom.
[src:baseball-positions/16-inch-softball] Play was encouraged by a reporter, George Hancock, who had been looking on.
[src:baseball-positions/16-inch-softball] Harvard and Yale students played the game while waiting to hear the results of the annual Harvard-Yale football game.
[src:baseball-positions/16-inch-softball] Until the turn of the 20th century, ball sizes ranged from 12 to 17 inches in circumference.
[src:baseball-positions/16-inch-softball] The 16-inch softball was eventually adopted in Chicago, perhaps because it did not travel as far as the popular 12- or 14-inch balls.
[src:baseball-positions/16-inch-softball] This also may have allowed for play on smaller playgrounds or even indoors, accommodating the Chicago landscape and climate.
[src:baseball-positions/16-inch-softball] Another possible advantage of the 16-inch ball was that it allowed everyone to play barehanded, and gloves were a rare luxury as the Great Depression hit Chicago particularly hard.
[src:baseball-positions/16-inch-softball] After the first national championship held in 1933 at the Century of Progress World's Fair, the sport grew in popularity.
[src:baseball-positions/16-inch-softball] A professional league was formed that lasted through the 1950s.
[src:baseball-positions/16-inch-softball] Teams drew crowds of over 10,000 each night.
[src:baseball-positions/16-inch-softball] Leagues continue today but not at the same level of popularity.
[src:baseball-positions/16-inch-softball] There are co-ed recreational leagues, competitive leagues and even a league for Chicago Public School students.
[src:baseball-positions/16-inch-softball] Many local organizations host regular season play, typically weekly games, as well as their own playoff systems.
[src:baseball-positions/16-inch-softball] National organizations, such as the NSA, host a variety of tournaments.
[src:baseball-positions/16-inch-softball] By placing well in NSA tournaments, teams can qualify and compete for the 16-inch softball world series.
[src:baseball-positions/16-inch-softball] Because local leagues may have slight variations in rules, the NSA world series is played by its own set of world series rules.
[src:baseball-positions/16-inch-softball] One notable change is that Chicago area players, who typically are not allowed to wear gloves, may choose to wear gloves in world series games.
[src:baseball-positions/16-inch-softball] Games are played with a deBeer Clincher 16" ball and gloves are used.
[src:baseball-positions/16-inch-softball] In 1996 Al Maag and Tony Reibel established the 16" Softball Hall of Fame.
[src:baseball-positions/16-inch-softball] Since inception, the organization has held annual inductee dinners attended by over 600 guests.
[src:baseball-positions/16-inch-softball] There is a museum in Forest Park, Illinois, a suburb of Chicago.
[src:baseball-positions/16-inch-softball] 16inchsoftballhof.com The Chicago 16" Softball Hall of Fame is a registered 501(c) not-for-profit organization.
[src:baseball-positions/16-inch-softball] The game can be seen being played in multiple scenes in the 1986 film *About Last Night*, whose storyline was set in Chicago.
[src:baseball-positions/ace-baseball] In baseball, an **ace** is a starting pitcher considered the best pitcher on a team's starting rotation.
[src:baseball-positions/ace-baseball] Barring injury or exceptional circumstances, a team's ace typically starts on Opening Day.
[src:baseball-positions/ace-baseball] In addition, aces are usually preferred to start crucial playoff games, sometimes on three days' rest.
[src:baseball-positions/ace-baseball] The term may be a derivation of the nickname of Asa Brainard (real first name: "Asahel"), a 19th-century star pitcher, who was sometimes referred to as "Ace".
[src:baseball-positions/ace-baseball] In the early days of baseball, the term *ace* was used to refer to a run.
[src:baseball-positions/ace-baseball] Modern baseball analysts and fans have started using the term *ace* to refer to the elite pitchers in the game, not necessarily to the best starting pitcher on each team.
[src:baseball-positions/ace-baseball] For example, the April 27, 1981, *Sports Illustrated* cover was captioned "The Amazing A's and Their Five Aces" to describe the starting rotation of the 1981 Oakland Athletics, which featured Mike Norris, Rick Langford, Matt Keough, Steve McCatty, and Brian Kingman.
[src:baseball-positions/appeal-play] In baseball, an **appeal play** occurs when a member of the defensive team calls the attention of an umpire to an infraction that they would otherwise ignore.
[src:baseball-positions/appeal-play] To properly execute a live ball appeal, a fielder must, with a live ball, tag the runner or base in question and communicate to the umpire what the infraction was and which runner committed the infraction.
[src:baseball-positions/appeal-play] Such communication may be non-verbal, implicit, or assumed—so long as the intent of the fielder is clear to the umpire.
[src:baseball-positions/appeal-play] Contrary to popular belief, an appeal out is not a force out unless it is regarding a missed force base.
[src:baseball-positions/appeal-play] For example, if a runner from third base tags up and scores, but a runner from second base leaves too early, failing to tag up, and then is put out on the appeal, the run counts if it was scored before the appeal by the fielders.
[src:baseball-positions/appeal-play] Rare situations with a viable appeal on a runner who misses his force base require the umpire to recognize an apparent fourth out.
[src:baseball-positions/appeal-play] Umpires will only rule on legal appeals.
[src:baseball-positions/appeal-play] A potential appeal is *viable* if the appeal is legal and the umpire knows that the runner has indeed committed an infraction and will be called out if the appeal is executed by a fielder.
[src:baseball-positions/appeal-play] Suppose that runners are on first and third base, and the batter hits a fly ball.
[src:baseball-positions/appeal-play] The runner on third tags up, leaving third base immediately after the outfielder touches the ball.
[src:baseball-positions/appeal-play] The runner seems to score, beating the throw home, but failing to touch home plate.
[src:baseball-positions/appeal-play] The runner proceeds into his dugout without again attempting to touch home base.
[src:baseball-positions/appeal-play] The runner on first base stays at first base, and action becomes relaxed while the ball is in the infield.
[src:baseball-positions/appeal-play] The fielders now suspect that the runner left third base too early and also missed the plate.
[src:baseball-positions/appeal-play] Suppose then that a fielder, with the live ball, touches home base and says to the nearest umpire, "I think they never touched home." This is a legal and viable appeal, and so the umpire should call the runner out and direct that his run shall not count.
[src:baseball-positions/appeal-play] Since the ball was live (and indeed must be for appeals to be legal), the runner from first could have attempted to advance at any time during the appeals.
[src:baseball-positions/appeal-play] If the defense attempts to play on that runner, their opportunity to appeal the runner from third base is lost, and the run would count regardless of any subsequent attempt to appeal.
[src:baseball-positions/appeal-play] A member of the defensive team may appeal to the umpire when a batter bats out of turn.
[src:baseball-positions/appeal-play] The umpire then enforces the penalty for batting out of turn, if any.
[src:baseball-positions/appeal-play] The ball must be live for this as for any appeal.
[src:baseball-positions/appeal-play] After the appeal is made, the umpire will usually signal "Time" and figure out whether the appeal is successful.
[src:baseball-positions/appeal-play] The field umpire then signals whether the batter swung, and such a judgment must, by rule, prevail.
[src:baseball-positions/appeal-play] The umpire asked is usually the first-base umpire (or third-base, if the batter is left-handed).
[src:baseball-positions/appeal-play] The plate umpire is not required to ask for assistance if they believe the request is making a farce of the game.
[src:baseball-positions/appeal-play] If the bat barely left the shoulder of the batter and the catcher appeals the "no-swing" call, the umpire will probably deny the appeal.
[src:baseball-positions/appeal-play] This procedure was introduced because it is commonplace for a plate umpire to be unable to see some swings.
[src:baseball-positions/appeal-play] A manager may ask an umpire to request assistance on other plays where another umpire had a better view, but the umpire is not required to do so.
[src:baseball-positions/appeal-play] Such requests are common when a close home run or foul ball call is disputed, or when determining the accuracy of a close catch or no catch call.
[src:baseball-positions/appeal-play] In such a case, the plate umpire would put a new ball in play, and after the ball became live by rule, the defense could appeal the missed base.
[src:baseball-positions/assist-baseball] In baseball, an **assist** (denoted by **A**) is a defensive statistic, baseball being one of the few sports in which the *defensive* team controls the ball.
[src:baseball-positions/assist-baseball] An assist is credited to every defensive player who fields or touches the ball (after it has been hit by the batter) prior to the recording of a putout, even if the contact was unintentional.
[src:baseball-positions/assist-baseball] For example, if a ball strikes a player's leg and bounces off him to another fielder, who tags the baserunner, the first player is credited with an assist.
[src:baseball-positions/assist-baseball] A fielder can receive a maximum of one assist per out recorded.
[src:baseball-positions/assist-baseball] An assist is also credited if a putout would have occurred, had another fielder not committed an error.
[src:baseball-positions/assist-baseball] For example, a shortstop might field a ground ball cleanly, but the first baseman might drop his throw.
[src:baseball-positions/assist-baseball] In this case, an error would be charged to the first baseman, and the shortstop would be credited with an assist.
[src:baseball-positions/assist-baseball] If a pitcher records a strikeout where the third strike is caught by the catcher, the pitcher is not credited with an assist.
[src:baseball-positions/assist-baseball] However, if the batter becomes a baserunner on a dropped third strike and the pitcher is involved in recording a putout by fielding the ball and either tagging the runner out or throwing to first base for the out, the pitcher is credited with an assist just as any other fielder would be.
[src:baseball-positions/assist-baseball] Assists are an important statistic for outfielders, as a play often occurs when a baserunner on the opposing team attempts to advance on the basepaths when the ball is hit to the outfield (even on a caught fly ball that results in an out; see tag up).
[src:baseball-positions/assist-baseball] It is the outfielder's job to field the ball and make an accurate throw to another fielder who is covering the base before the runner reaches it.
[src:baseball-positions/assist-baseball] The fielder then attempts to tag the runner out.
[src:baseball-positions/assist-baseball] This is especially important if the runner was trying to reach home plate, as the assist and tag prevent the baserunner from scoring a run.
[src:baseball-positions/assist-baseball] Assists are much rarer for outfielders than infielders (with the exception of first basemen) because the play is harder to make, and also because outfielder assist situations occur less often than the traditional ground-ball assist for a shortstop, second baseman, or third baseman.
[src:baseball-positions/assist-baseball] However, as a result, outfield assists are worth far more than infield assists, and tell more about an outfielder's throwing arm than infielder assists do.
[src:baseball-positions/assist-baseball] In recent years, some sabermetricians have begun referring to assists by outfielders as **baserunner kills**.
[src:baseball-positions/assist-baseball] Some sabermetricians are also using *baserunner holds* as a statistic to measure outfield arms.
[src:baseball-positions/assist-baseball] A baserunner hold occurs when the baserunner does not attempt to advance an extra base on an outfielder out of concern of being thrown out by a strong, accurate throw.
[src:baseball-positions/assist-baseball] This can be combined with baserunner kills for better accuracy, as runners often do not try for an extra base when an outfielder with an excellent arm is playing.
[src:baseball-positions/at-bat] In baseball, an **at bat** (**AB**) or **time at bat** is a batter's turn batting against a pitcher.
[src:baseball-positions/at-bat] An at bat is different from a plate appearance.
[src:baseball-positions/at-bat] A batter is credited with a plate appearance regardless of what happens upon completion of his turn at bat, but a batter is charged with an at bat only if that plate appearance does not have one of the results enumerated below.
[src:baseball-positions/at-bat] While at bats are used to calculate certain statistics, including batting average and slugging percentage, players can qualify for the season-ending rankings in these categories only if they accumulate 502 plate appearances during the season.
[src:baseball-positions/at-bat] In addition, if the inning ends during an at bat (due to the third out being made by a runner caught stealing, for example), no at bat or plate appearance will result because neither were completed.
[src:baseball-positions/at-bat] An at bat is a specific type of plate appearance in which the batter stands at the plate intending to put the ball in play and get on base.
[src:baseball-positions/at-bat] This is why at bats, and not plate appearances, are used to calculate batting average, as plate appearances in general can result in many outcomes that do not necessarily involve putting the ball in play, and batting average specifically measures a batter's contact hitting.
[src:baseball-positions/at-bat] Pete Rose had 14,053 career at bats, the all-time major league and National League record.
[src:baseball-positions/at-bat] The American League record is held by Carl Yastrzemski, whose 11,988 career at bats were all in the AL.
[src:baseball-positions/at-bat] The single season record is held by Jimmy Rollins, who had 716 at bats in 2007.
[src:baseball-positions/at-bat] Willie Wilson, Ichiro Suzuki and Juan Samuel also had more than 700 at bats in a season.
[src:baseball-positions/at-bat] 14 players share the single game record of 11 at bats in a single game, all of which were extra inning games.
[src:baseball-positions/at-bat] In games of 9 innings or fewer, the record is 7 at bats and has occurred more than 200 times.
[src:baseball-positions/at-bat] The team record for most at bats in a single season is 5,781 by the 1997 Boston Red Sox.
[src:baseball-positions/at-bat] "At bat", "up", "up at bat", and "at the plate" are all phrases describing a batter who is facing the pitcher.
[src:baseball-positions/at-bat] Just because a player is described as being "at bat" in this sense, he will not necessarily be given an at bat in his statistics; the phrase actually signifies a plate appearance (assuming it is eventually completed).
[src:baseball-positions/at-bat] This ambiguous terminology is usually clarified by context.
[src:baseball-positions/at-bat] To refer explicitly to a statistical "at bat", the term "official at bat" is sometimes used.
[src:baseball-positions/at-bat] Official Baseball Rule 5.06(c) provides that "[a] batter has legally completed his *time at bat* when he is put out or becomes a runner" (emphasis added).
[src:baseball-positions/at-bat] The "time at bat" defined in this rule is more commonly referred to as a plate appearance, and the playing rules (Rules 1 through 8) uses the phrase "time at bat" in this sense.
[src:baseball-positions/at-bat] In contrast, the scoring rules use the phrase "time at bat" to refer to the statistic **at bat**, defined in Rule 9.02(a)(1), but sometimes uses the phrase "official time at bat" or refers back to Rule 9.02(a)(1) when mentioning the statistic.
[src:baseball-positions/athletic-trainer] An **athletic trainer** is a certified and licensed health care provider who practices in the field of sports medicine.
[src:baseball-positions/athletic-trainer] Athletic training has been recognized by the American Medical Association (AMA) as an allied health care profession since 1990.
[src:baseball-positions/athletic-trainer] "Athletic training encompasses the prevention, examination, diagnosis, treatment, and rehabilitation of emergent, acute or chronic injuries and medical conditions.
[src:baseball-positions/athletic-trainer] To become an athletic trainer, one must have a master's degree from an accredited professional level education program and then sit for and pass the Board of Certification (BOC) examination.
[src:baseball-positions/athletic-trainer] Since 2023, all accredited professional programs have been required to provide a master's level education.
[src:baseball-positions/athletic-trainer] Each state then has its own regulatory agencies that control the practice of athletic training in their state.
[src:baseball-positions/athletic-trainer] Emerging settings for athletic training include surgical fellowship opportunities.
[src:baseball-positions/athletic-trainer] The Commission on Accreditation of Athletic Training Education (CAATE) oversees the curriculum standards of all accredited Professional (entry level) and all the institutions.
[src:baseball-positions/athletic-trainer] The standards dictate the content of both didactic and clinical practice portions of the educational program.
[src:baseball-positions/athletic-trainer] There are several post-professional masters-level athletic training programs.
[src:baseball-positions/athletic-trainer] These programs are for credentialed athletic trainers who desire to become scholars, researchers, and advanced practice professionals.
[src:baseball-positions/athletic-trainer] Schools with post-professional athletic training masters programs include: A.T.
[src:baseball-positions/athletic-trainer] There are doctoral programs in athletic training, each with different curricular emphasis.
[src:baseball-positions/athletic-trainer] Athletic training program in doctoral education is offered by the University of Idaho, Florida International University, A.T.
[src:baseball-positions/athletic-trainer] Still University, Indiana State University, Ohio University, Temple University, and Moravian University.
[src:baseball-positions/athletic-trainer] Athletic trainers treat a broad population, from the amateur and professional athlete to the typical patient in need of orthopaedic rehabilitative care.
[src:baseball-positions/athletic-trainer] Services rendered by the athletic trainer take place in a wide variety of settings and venues.
[src:baseball-positions/automated-ball-strike-system] The **Automated Ball-Strike** (**ABS**) System is a system that automates the interpretation of whether pitches are in the strike zone in baseball games.
[src:baseball-positions/automated-ball-strike-system] It is currently used by the KBO League in South Korea, and by Minor League Baseball (MiLB) and Major League Baseball (MLB) in the United States and Canada.
[src:baseball-positions/automated-ball-strike-system] In MLB and MiLB, it is used to enable player challenges of umpire calls of balls and strikes, while in the KBO League and previously in MiLB, it calls pitches automatically.
[src:baseball-positions/automated-ball-strike-system] The independent Atlantic League first used ABS, nicknamed "robot umpires", during its 2019 all-star game.
[src:baseball-positions/automated-ball-strike-system] Umpires used earpieces to receive ball-strike calls using TrackMan technology.
[src:baseball-positions/automated-ball-strike-system] Umpires could make a call based on the automated message, or could make their own call if the automated system malfunctioned or registered a call with which the umpire disagreed.
[src:baseball-positions/automated-ball-strike-system] The Arizona Fall League began using ABS during its 2021 season.
[src:baseball-positions/automated-ball-strike-system] The technology drew complaints from players and fans for its treatment of breaking balls as strikes even when they break and drop out of the strike zone.
[src:baseball-positions/automated-ball-strike-system] Human umpires were obligated to make a call based on ABS, and players could be ejected if they contested a call, as with all ball-strike calls.
[src:baseball-positions/automated-ball-strike-system] The Florida State League, a low-A league in Florida, used ABS in its 2021 season.
[src:baseball-positions/automated-ball-strike-system] The Major League Baseball Umpires Association (MLBUA) agreed to cooperate and assist if MLB commissioner Rob Manfred decided to use ABS at the major league level, as part of the MLBUA's contract with MLB in 2020.
[src:baseball-positions/automated-ball-strike-system] Five Triple-A baseball stadiums used ABS in 2022, and the system expanded to all stadiums at that level in 2023.
[src:baseball-positions/automated-ball-strike-system] In 2023, Triple-A baseball used ABS with and without a challenge system; without a challenge system, human umpires relayed automated calls, and with the system, an automated call would be used only when a team requested a challenge.
[src:baseball-positions/automated-ball-strike-system] In 2024, Triple-A teams that played six-game series first used ABS without a challenge system for the first three games, and with challenges for the latter three; starting on June 25, MLB announced that only the challenge system would be used.
[src:baseball-positions/automated-ball-strike-system] In 2024, 51% of challenges in Triple-A games were successful.
[src:baseball-positions/automated-ball-strike-system] South Korea's KBO League started to use ABS in its 2024 season.
[src:baseball-positions/automated-ball-strike-system] Unlike in MLB, KBO uses ABS to call balls and strikes automatically.
[src:baseball-positions/automated-ball-strike-system] ABS was in place for Spring Training before the 2025 MLB season.
[src:baseball-positions/automated-ball-strike-system] Thirteen Spring Training ballparks, used as home fields by 19 clubs, are equipped with ABS technology.
[src:baseball-positions/automated-ball-strike-system] MLB implemented ABS as a challenge system; human umpires make initial calls, which pitchers, catchers, and batters may challenge.
[src:baseball-positions/automated-ball-strike-system] MLB used ABS for the 2025 All-Star Game, with a similar configuration to spring training: each team had two challenges, which could be requested by the pitcher, catcher, or hitter immediately after a call.
[src:baseball-positions/automated-ball-strike-system] Cal Raleigh, the first player to request an ABS challenge in an MLB All-Star Game, successfully challenged the umpire's ball call of a pitch he caught from Tarik Skubal, resulting in Manny Machado being called out on strikes.
[src:baseball-positions/automated-ball-strike-system] Jacob Wilson was the first batter to challenge a call, successfully getting a pitch from MacKenzie Gore changed from a strike to a ball.
[src:baseball-positions/automated-ball-strike-system] In September 2025, MLB's competition committee approved use of ABS beginning with the 2026 season, with similar processes to those used in Spring Training and the All-Star Game.
[src:baseball-positions/automated-ball-strike-system] Each team starts with two challenges, retains a challenge if it is successful, and may receive additional challenges in extra innings.
[src:baseball-positions/automated-ball-strike-system] On March 25, 2026, Opening Day, New York Yankees shortstop José Caballero made the first ABS challenge in an MLB regular season game, challenging Bill Miller's strike call on Logan Webb's first pitch to him in the fourth inning.
[src:baseball-positions/automated-ball-strike-system] Caballero's challenge was unsuccessful, and the strike call was upheld.
[src:baseball-positions/automated-ball-strike-system] The following day, Francisco Álvarez, catcher for the New York Mets, made the first successful ABS challenge in an MLB regular season game, after he challenged a ball call on a pitch by Freddy Peralta.
[src:baseball-positions/automated-ball-strike-system] The call was changed to a strike, resulting in the batter, Oneil Cruz, striking out.
[src:baseball-positions/automated-ball-strike-system] In May 2026, the NCAA baseball rules committee approved a request by the Southeastern Conference (SEC) for permission to use ABS as part of its conference tournament; it will utilize similar rules to ABS in MLB, except that teams will begin with three challenges instead of two.
[src:baseball-positions/automated-ball-strike-system] On May 19, 2026, Mississippi catcher Austin Fawley made the first ABS challenge in a college baseball game, challenging a ball call on a pitch by Mississippi pitcher Will Libbert in the top of the first inning.
[src:baseball-positions/automated-ball-strike-system] The challenge was unsuccessful, and the call stood.
[src:baseball-positions/automated-ball-strike-system] As implemented by MLB, ABS uses Hawk-Eye camera technology, and a private 5G network by T-Mobile to transmit data.
[src:baseball-positions/automated-ball-strike-system] T-Mobile also serves as presenting sponsor for reviews.
[src:baseball-positions/automated-ball-strike-system] Reviews are shown on screens in stadiums and on broadcasts for home viewers.
[src:baseball-positions/automated-ball-strike-system] MLB has experimented with the size of the strike zone, a three-dimensional space defined in the official rules of Major League Baseball, as used by ABS.
[src:baseball-positions/automated-ball-strike-system] The league started with a width of 19 inches (480 mm) in 2022, then decreased it to 17 inches (430 mm), the same width as home plate.
[src:baseball-positions/automated-ball-strike-system] The top of the zone was 51% of a batter's height in 2022 and 2023, then raised to 53.5% in 2024 after pitchers' complaints.
[src:baseball-positions/automated-ball-strike-system] The bottom of the strike zone was originally set at 28% of the batter's height, and has been 27% since 2022.
[src:baseball-positions/automated-ball-strike-system] ABS's use of height in its strike zone led the league to measure players more precisely, without manipulation by team personnel, in 2026; of the 430 hitters on Opening Day rosters in 2026, 225 had listed heights at least 1 inch (25 mm) shorter than in 2024 or 2025.
[src:baseball-positions/automated-ball-strike-system] ABS makes its decision when the ball is at the midpoint of the plate, 8.5 inches (220 mm) from the front and back, despite MLB rules stating that a pitch is a strike if it crosses any part of a 3D solid with home plate as its base.
[src:baseball-positions/automated-ball-strike-system] The ABS strike zone does not change based on the batter's stance.
[src:baseball-positions/automated-ball-strike-system] In MLB, only the batter, pitcher, or catcher may challenge a ball or strike call, doing so by tapping his cap or helmet immediately after an umpire's call.
[src:baseball-positions/automated-ball-strike-system] Each team gets two challenges per game, but loses a challenge if an original call is upheld after review.
[src:baseball-positions/automated-ball-strike-system] In extra innings, a team that begins an inning with no challenges will receive one challenge to use or carry forward; it will not receive additional challenges if it has at least one at the start of an extra inning.
[src:baseball-positions/automated-ball-strike-system] Players must make a decision on their own, without assistance from other players or team personnel, such as coaches or managers.
[src:baseball-positions/automated-ball-strike-system] Unlike instant replay challenges, managers may not challenge a ball-strike call.
[src:baseball-positions/automated-ball-strike-system] Challenges are not permitted while a position player is pitching.
[src:baseball-positions/automated-ball-strike-system] ABS reports pitch locations in increments of 0.1 inches (2.5 mm), although some players have expressed concerns about the system's margin of error.
[src:baseball-positions/automated-ball-strike-system] MLB officials told *The Athletic* that the league has 95 percent confidence that ABS would a report a pitch to within 0.39 inches (9.9 mm), and 99 percent confidence that the location would be within 0.48 inches (12 mm) of its recorded position.
[src:baseball-positions/automated-ball-strike-system] During 2026 spring training games, the league said that the median margin of error on any given pitch was about 0.16 inches (4.1 mm).
[src:baseball-positions/automated-ball-strike-system] MLB's internal evaluations of umpire accuracy use a buffer zone on the periphery of the strike zone, in which calls remain unchanged due to measurement uncertainty, but ABS has no buffer zone.
[src:baseball-positions/automated-ball-strike-system] In MLB, an ABS challenge typically takes less than 15 seconds.
[src:baseball-positions/automated-ball-strike-system] Through the first two and a half weeks of the 2026 season, a nine-inning game took an average of 2 hours, 42 minutes to complete, up from 2:38 in the prior season, but still much shorter than 3:10 in 2021, the last MLB season without the pitch clock.
[src:baseball-positions/automated-ball-strike-system] MLB started testing ABS because of fans' strong feelings about inaccurate umpire calls of balls and strikes, which can affect the outcome of games.
[src:baseball-positions/automated-ball-strike-system] According to an MLB poll in 2024, 61% of team personnel (including players) and 47% of fans preferred a challenge system for ball-strike calls, 28% of team personnel and 30% of fans preferred not to use ABS at all, and 11% of team personnel and 23% of fans wanted full automation.
[src:baseball-positions/automated-ball-strike-system] Players and managers have sometimes objected to ball-strike calls even after an ABS review, but doing so still risks ejection from the game.
[src:baseball-positions/automated-ball-strike-system] "Nobody complains about anything anymore with the strike zone because there's nothing to complain about," said Toby Gardenhire, manager of the St.
[src:baseball-positions/automated-ball-strike-system] Players observed that catchers could no longer frame pitches to try to get strike calls on pitches outside the zone.
[src:baseball-positions/automated-ball-strike-system] Players in Triple-A have typically saved their challenges for higher-leverage situations; more than 8% of pitches on a 3–2 count were challenged, whereas only 1.6% of first pitches were.
[src:baseball-positions/automated-ball-strike-system] "Your heart rate goes through the roof", said Michael Toglia of the Colorado Rockies, about calling a challenge during his time in Triple-A.
[src:baseball-positions/automated-ball-strike-system] Tyler Glasnow of the Los Angeles Dodgers said that ABS challenges were "the most fun part of the game" during a rehab assignment in Triple-A, because when a player challenged a call successfully, they felt "vindicated".
[src:baseball-positions/automated-ball-strike-system] Baseball broadcasters have redesigned their augmented reality strike zone graphics as a result of ABS.
[src:baseball-positions/automated-ball-strike-system] The league still permits broadcasters to show a box approximating the strike zone, but does not let broadcasters indicate where the pitch is when it crosses the plate during live action, to discourage viewers from signaling to players that they should challenge a call.
[src:baseball-positions/automated-ball-strike-system] After the first weekend of the 2026 MLB season, Jeff Passan wrote, "Not only does ABS work, it makes the game better." In the season's first 48 games, 94 calls were overturned, out of 175 challenges.
[src:baseball-positions/automated-ball-strike-system] Fans in stadiums and television broadcasters had enthusiastically embraced the challenge system, leading Passan to wonder whether it should be used for all ball–strike calls in the future.
[src:baseball-positions/automated-ball-strike-system] Former MLB umpires have suggested that current umpires would adjust their ball–strike calls in anticipation of ABS challenges.
[src:baseball-positions/automated-ball-strike-system] "As an umpire, what you're trying to do is not get overturned", said Dale Scott, a retired MLB umpire.
[src:baseball-positions/automated-ball-strike-system] Joe West, another retired umpire, expressed concerns with ABS's accuracy.
[src:baseball-positions/automated-ball-strike-system] Retired umpire Jim Joyce called ABS "the best scenario right now", because it is aiming to get more calls correct, and because it is used as a challenge system, not as a fully automated pitch calling system.
[src:baseball-positions/automated-ball-strike-system] In minor leagues and in MLB, the walk rate has increased significantly after ABS was introduced.
[src:baseball-positions/automated-ball-strike-system] MLB's walk rate early in the 2026 season was at 9.9% of plate appearances, up from the typical 8% to 9%, and on pace for the highest walk rate since the mound was lowered in 1969.
[src:baseball-positions/automated-ball-strike-system] Hitters began the 2026 MLB season by swinging on 46.2% of pitches, down from 47.2% to 47.8% in prior seasons, and on pace for the lowest swing rate in a 162-game season since 2014.
[src:baseball-positions/baseball-positions] In the sport of baseball, each of the nine players on a team is assigned a particular **fielding position** when it is their turn to play defense.
[src:baseball-positions/baseball-positions] Each position conventionally has an associated number, for use in scorekeeping by the official scorer: 1 (pitcher), 2 (catcher), 3 (first baseman), 4 (second baseman), 5 (third baseman), 6 (shortstop), 7 (left fielder), 8 (center fielder), and 9 (right fielder).
[src:baseball-positions/baseball-positions] Collectively, these positions are usually grouped into three groups: the outfield (left field, center field, and right field), the infield (first base, second base, third base, and shortstop), and the battery (pitcher and catcher).
[src:baseball-positions/baseball-positions] Fielders must be able to catch the ball well, as catching batted balls before they bounce is one way they can put the batter out, as well as create opportunities to prevent the advance of, and put out other runners.
[src:baseball-positions/baseball-positions] Fielders often have to run, dive, and slide a great deal in the act of reaching, stopping, and retrieving a hit ball, and then setting themselves up to transfer the ball, all with the end goal of getting the ball as quickly as possible to another fielder.
[src:baseball-positions/baseball-positions] They also run the risk of colliding with incoming runners during a tag attempt at a base.
[src:baseball-positions/baseball-positions] Fielders may have different responsibilities depending on the game situation.
[src:baseball-positions/baseball-positions] For example, when an outfielder is attempting to throw the ball from near the fence to one of the bases, an infielder may need to "cut off" the throw and then act as a relay thrower to help the ball cover its remaining distance to the target destination.
[src:baseball-positions/baseball-positions] As a group, the outfielders are responsible for preventing home runs by reaching over the fence (and potentially doing a wall climb) for fly balls that are catchable.
[src:baseball-positions/baseball-positions] The infielders are the ones who generally handle plays that involve tagging a base or runner, and also need quick reflexes in order to catch a batted ball before it leaves the infield.
[src:baseball-positions/baseball-positions] The pitcher and catcher have special responsibilities to prevent base stealing, as they are the ones who handle the ball whenever it has not been hit.
[src:baseball-positions/baseball-positions] The catcher will also sometimes attempt to block the plate in order to prevent a run being scored.
